No comment on the associated outlook for its legitimacy, likely impact, or participation rates (and these considerations are not what we’re forecasting on here strictly speaking).

"TUNIS, June 20 (Reuters) - The head of Tunisia's constitution committee delivered the draft of a new constitution to the president Kais Saied on Monday, the presidency said."
The date is set, let's see if it goes ahead.

"At the urging of external donors, Presi­dent Saied revealed his political roadmap in December 2021 after months of silence. It included an online survey on central politi­cal, social and economic topics that was conducted in early 2022. On the basis of its findings, hand-picked individuals and organisations are currently advising the president on the drafting of a new constitution, to be completed by the end of June. A referendum on 25 July 2022 will approve the new constitution."
No news on constitutional draft, but judges' strike heads into the second week.
Expat voting is in process and public sentiment for the referendum is high. Strong momentum.

In my update, I'm going to hold what I have for my percentage. The average right now is 70%. There are two specific things that I will add to my original snipit and why I'll hold what I have. First, Tunisian President Kais Saied threatened to suspend the country's membership of the Venice Commission and expel its representatives, after it published a report criticizing his plan to hold a referendum on a new constitution. Lastly, Tunisia officially stated that it will hold a constitutional referendum for a "new republic" on July 25 in defiance of critics who warn he wants to establish an autocracy.

Yes. There is a 75% change that there will be a referendum before August 1, 2022. The latest move, back in February 2022, President Saied dissolved the Supreme Judicial Council. President Saied has control of the central government and most of the military. And has been periodically consolidating power since July 2021 when he suspended parliament and ousted the Prime Minister. There has been little push back from the international community to include the U.S. Further, despite increasing protests from Tunisians, there has been little to no yield of power or control by President Saied – a man who compares himself to Charles de Gaulle. However, Tunisia's powerful general labor union has recently stated that it would hold a national strike over wages and the economy. This strike could lead to more uproar and potentially spark a revolution led by the people overthrowing the president and his authoritarian dictatorship. However, the likelihood is low.
Since a specific date was announced, I’m reconsidering as that makes it marginally harder to back away.

Tunisian President Kais Saied said that a referendum was going to be held on July 25th, 2022. But given his repeated broken promises regarding infrastructure funding and social change, it would be no surprise if this referendum was ignored entirely. Do I think it could happen sooner than August 1st or July 25th? Possibly, but only if something major happened i.e. blatant abuse of power. However, I believe it will either happen in July or it will not happen at all.
Staying on the low side until the constitution is actually drafted.
Apparently, the committee to prepare various reform bills has not yet even been assembled. ~ 3 months to go, so revising downwards.
This is Africa, who knows?

President Kais Saied needs to organize his referendum on the constitution to consolidate his grip on power, particularly as the opposition to his rule is becoming more vocal and as the economic situation is worsening. He has set June as his timeline to hold this referendum, however this sort of process is slippery, and he might not be able to get it done by that date. The referendum will be seen as a plebiscite for his rule, and if in the mean time opposition becomes too strong or vocal he might feel the need to postpone it.

The link below was a great resource. I lowered the probability of a referendum to a 51% probability from 57%. President Saied is seeing less and less support and his autocratic actions have undermined the progress of the democratic process thus far. On top of that, there is a real threat of economic collapse if agreements aren't reached on reforms, however President Saied is not consulting with groups "such as the workers’ union UGTT, the employers’ organization UTICA, and the agriculture union UTAP." Making it difficult, if not impossible to secure funding from organizations like the IMF.

It seems like President Saied is now capable of making decisions without consent or support from any political forces within Tunisia. This was exemplified less than 2 weeks ago when he dissolved the Supreme Judicial Council.

Revising forecast downward, at least until the ongoing “online public consultation” to inform the referendum is reported to conclude on schedule and without sparking any new significant protest events. This would be a first verifiable indication that the Saied roadmap/timeline might actually be followed. In parallel, one of the most important precursor indications of adherence to the July 25 timeframe will be how the opposition groups choose to act: whether or not the various groups choose to actually go along with the “roadmap” plan (with the aim of creating pro-democracy impacts from within the system Saied is trying to establish), or if they fight it more openly to try and impose their own alternative plan to exit the current unconstitutional/undemocratic situation. In the second scenario, there is obviously a much greater chance of unrest / circumstances that could cause delays of the referendum until “security is restored”.

Overall it seems that the President holds a fairly large constituency who believe and back his efforts. However, there are clear issues here which is why I only gave the referendum possibility a slightly higher probability. One issue is that the consultation that is currently being held by Tunisia is online and therefore not inclusive for those who don't have access to the internet, causing discontent. Another issue is the President's autocratic actions which have shifted Tunisia to a more centralized government. Both of these issues, along with others, have created a political divide in the country. With that being said, the President still has support and consultations are happening as he promised, which leads me to believe that the rest of the President's agenda would be carried out as promised as well.
As messy as the situation looks right now, so far the president has made sure his decisions & promises come through.

The current political situation in Tunisia is becoming increasingly tense. President Saied is not convincing Tunisians of his claim to power and stands on the brink of national bankruptcy according to the latest reports from Reuters. For Tunisia to still present a constitutional referendum before August 2022, the economy will need to stabilize and Saied will need to ensure Tunisians their freedom will be secure and their democracy will not fall apart. What appears is more likely to happen is civil unrest and uprisings which is why give 35% probability to the likelihood of a Tunisian constitutional referendum.

President Kais Saied he will hold a constitutional referendum before August 2022. Though legitimacy of the referendum may be in question it will happen, none the less. The suspension of parliament will stand until new elections are carried forward in Dec. 2022. Without their involvement the legitimacy may be in question but even in questionable form, I believe the referendum will occur.

The rationale behind my decision is that the current President, President Saied, has recently seized power through a self coup. If any new amendments or a new constitution counts as the criteria I could see the Tunisian government adopting new amendments to cement the current rule.
Yes. Some of the factors involved include his popularity rating, the Tunisian economy, and the opposition's will to pursue legal challenges to his rule.
There will be a stalling tactic, which may or may not succeed
The consultation portal is due to open tomorrow until March 20th. these dates being held will one key to the July 25th referendum. July 25th is 1 year since Saied sacked the parliament.

If "a" referendum is a low threshold to meet. A referendum could be held and it could all be manipulated and just amend the existing constitution without any real input. The real question is will Saied be president on 1 August 2023.

They have started a consultation process and schedules a date so it appears it is going to happen barring a material surprise (possible if the consultation has results the President does not like I suppose).
Will happen but later than claimed
I think it will possibly happen later
He must do for integrity and if just amendments count then the odds are high
Saied has shown autocratic tendencies and Covid provides a ready made excuse to delay.

Seems likely that Saied will push for a referendum on 25th July at this stage. No indication at this stage that he would row back on this - but allowing 10% chance that the political situation becomes more volatile by the middle of 2022.

As of now, July 25 2022 for the election seems to be a set situation. The leadership of (military and police, cares about eliminating the large political corruption) Tunisia are in a tough game, as they continue their struggle to create some kind of progress.

The guy wants to have the referendum, and he has a strong enough hold on power to get his way. Perhaps some black swan event might force a delay, but the date picked is a symbolic one, so it would need to be something pretty big.

The odds that Saied aren't president by August 2022 are very low given that he has military support. And given the perception of Tunisia as a democratic success story from the AS + I think Saied actually cares about the country. I think the odds of a referendum are pretty high. Things to look out for: he promised experts to draft a constitution before the referendum, Is it happening? With enough time to re-write a constitution? Also foreign direct investment into the country so bond markets most likely. All of this together, I think he will have the referendum, but will be watching those signals.

Mr. Saied has set himself up to make all decisions about everything, so there is no reason to believe that he won't make a bunch of decisions before the date of this referendum that annul or postpone it. And it is also possible that the Tunisian people will decide they are tired of him.
